    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2055948268" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2055948268" />
    <a title="M." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9075047-m"><img alt="M." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442965983p2/9075047.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2055948268?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="M." class="user" itemprop="url" name="M." href="/user/show/9075047-m">M.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780854966714" href="/book/show/3219691-silence-of-the-sea-le-silence-de-la-mer">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2055948268" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer132823832149060248">After watching the incredible Melville film adaptation of this work, I had to get ahold of a copy to read for myself. The screenplay turned out to be as close of an adaptation as you could come up with, but the read was still far and away worth the effort. <br/><br/>This story of a silent protest of occupation forces in 1940 France is more full of humanity than almost anything I&apos;ve ever read before. Where as most wartime writings focuses on the atrocities and corruption of human nature through the experie</span>
  <span id="freeText132823832149060248" style="display:none">After watching the incredible Melville film adaptation of this work, I had to get ahold of a copy to read for myself. The screenplay turned out to be as close of an adaptation as you could come up with, but the read was still far and away worth the effort. <br /><br />This story of a silent protest of occupation forces in 1940 France is more full of humanity than almost anything I've ever read before. Where as most wartime writings focuses on the atrocities and corruption of human nature through the experiences of war and warring, this piece focuses instead on the concessions and delusions of those who hear the rumor of war pacing the floor overhead and yet find themselves incapable of sinking into simple hatred. With only three characters, this booklet manages to portray startlingly honest versions of the caring and romantic people we know in life but have never found a place for in war stories.<br /><br />I understand that this was originally printed as an anonymous bound volume in occupied Paris, but I can't believe everyone still refers to it as a novel when it's only about 30 pages long. It covers an immense amount of ground, but novella would be a generous enough description.</span>
  <a data-text-id="132823832149060248" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

