    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3175597437" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3175597437" />
    <a title="Darrel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6217140-darrel"><img alt="Darrel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315274875p2/6217140.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3175597437?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Darrel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Darrel" href="/user/show/6217140-darrel">Darrel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780854963782" href="/book/show/332544.The_Silence_of_the_Sea_Le_Silence_de_la_mer">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3175597437" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9927911877270055047">Concisely written story that is comprised of only three main characters: an old man and his niece who are forced to share their home in France with an occupying German Wehrmacht officer. The two use the only tactic that they have at their disposal to resist against the officer - silence. And indeed, they do not speak a word to him at all during his stay. The German officer, Werner von Ebrennac, speaks to them each day or night in uninterrupted soliloquies, to break the silence. His conversation </span>
  <span id="freeText9927911877270055047" style="display:none">Concisely written story that is comprised of only three main characters: an old man and his niece who are forced to share their home in France with an occupying German Wehrmacht officer. The two use the only tactic that they have at their disposal to resist against the officer - silence. And indeed, they do not speak a word to him at all during his stay. The German officer, Werner von Ebrennac, speaks to them each day or night in uninterrupted soliloquies, to break the silence. His conversation reveals him to be an educated man, a music lover and someone who has cultivated a deep love of France during the course of his life. He also believes that the inevitable union of France and Germany (due to the occupation) will be embraced by both countries. <br /><br />The gist of the tale of this novella lies in how each of them react to disturbing discoveries- in particular Ebrennac - after he attends a party for German officers, then returns 'home' and shares with the old man and his niece what his encounters and conversations with those at the party revealed. It's interesting to see a story of a Nazi depicted in a sympathetic viewpoint, one who is also both humane and passionate and then suffers the most devastating of revelations. A very memorable and rewarding story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9927911877270055047" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


